The role of Doppler sonography in assessment of malignant trophoblastic disease. An observational study on the role of Doppler sonography in the assessment of patients with malignant trophoblastic disease was performed in an Oncology Unit of a University teaching hospital. A total of 32 consecutive patients referred for chemotherapy were recruited. Twenty-three non-pregnant and 18 women in the first trimester of pregnancy acted as controls. The patients were prospectively followed-up for 2 years. It was found that the uterine arterial resistance index and pulsatility index in patients who required chemotherapy were significantly lower when compared with the non-pregnant and pregnant controls (Student t-test